 This article currently links to a large number of disambiguation pages (check | fix). Please help direct these ambiguous links to articles dealing with the specific meaning intended. Read the FAQ.   (October 2014) 






 This article appears to be written like an advertisement.  Please help improve it by rewriting promotional content from a neutral point of view and removing any inappropriate external links. (October 2014) 


Royalty Exchange is an American company where royalty owners have the ability to monetize their royalties and investors seeking to purchase alternative assets may invest in them.  It is a centralized marketplace and online auction where investors and owners of royalty collections may buy and sell royalties as alternative investments including music royalties and film royalties, patent and IP (intellectual property) royalties, trade secret royalties, renewable energy royalties, solar energy royalties, technology licensing royalties, book publishing royalties, franchise royalties, copyright royalties and agriculture royalties.[1][2]
Royalty Exchange offers an online auction platform that provides investors with an overview of royalty income data as well as full details and legal documentation regarding all presented assets. After an online auction for a royalty asset has closed, the winning bidder or investor, is provided a percentage of ownership and the right to collect a stream of future royalty payments.  Royalty owners may sell any percentage of their royalties and are permitted to set the reserve price and minimum bid amount. 

 File:Roylaty Exchange.jpg   

Background
Royalty Exchange was founded in 2011 in Raleigh, North Carolina.[1] and was launched by industry insiders who identified a need for a royalties-based online marketplace. The online platform provides asset owners flexibility to monetize a select portion, or the entirety, of their royalty streams, raising expedited capital for their professional or personal finance needs. [3] The founding team was lead by Sean Peace, serial tech entrepreneur and CEO, Reggie Calloway, singer/songwriter and 5-time Grammy nominated artist, as well as Wilson Owens, former band manager.[2]
The idea behind Royalty Exchange evolved after Peace’s communication with a former professor of the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill and aspiring songwriter, whom he had met while attending the university. During his discussion with the former professor, Peace discovered that post-retirement, she planned to sell her catalog of music royalties.  A songwriter’s catalog consists of the royalty interest in the artist’s work for sale, packaged to be sold to investors. He used the idea of selling a catalog based on a financial multiple of how much it made during prior years and integrated the auction mechanics like those of SongVest, into forming an online marketplace to buy and sell royalties of all kinds.[4]
Royalty Exchange consists of a team of professionals including Molly Pennington, Director of Operations, Sean Daley, VP of Marketing, Brian Casto, VP of Sales and Business Development, Reggie Calloway, VP of West Coast Sales, Preston Sullivan, VP of East Coast Sales, Rusty Harmon, VP of Sales and Mark Paris., Lead Developer.  The company’s board of advisors includes Jonathan Hoenig, Managing Member of Capitallstpig Hedge Fund LLC, Tom Lipsky, Music LLC Owner and President, Don Perry, Entertainment Industry Consultant and Business Advisor, Klaus Lovegreen, Owner at Evershift and Founder of AME Info, Martin Diessner, Co-Founder of Flip Media and Tech Investor, Hans Bald, Chief Executive Officer of 20 Gates Management, and Josh Brog, Managing Director of 20 Gates Management.[5]

 History 
The first successfully completed online auction featured on the Royalty Exchange website began on July 2, 2011, and closed on July 16, 2011. The online auction included royalties of Disney song writer Frank Churchill’s catalog.[6]  The catalog consists of songs from Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (“Heigh Ho,” “Whistle While You Work,” “I’m Wishing” and “Someday My Prince Will Come”), Dumbo (“Baby Mine” and “Pink Elephants on Parade”) and Bambi (“Love is a Song” and “Little April Shower”).[4]
Throughout the company’s growth, numerous online auctions have been successfully closed including the $85,000 sale of 100% of the songwriter’s share of ASCAP public performance royalties generated by Frank Sinatra’s, “A Nightingale Sings in Berkley Square,” and other compositions written by Manning Sherwin; the $156,000 sale of 50% of the writer’s share of BMI public performance royalties generated from a collection of over 98 songs by R&B singer-songwriter and producer Kashif; the $26,000 sale of 100% of Cheryl Cook’s BMI writer’s share of public performance royalties to 31 tracks including songs recorded by Jennifer Lopez, Sugarhill Gang and more; accumulated royalty-produced assets from songs by Preston Glass, Edmund Clement and other previous sales which can be viewed on the Royalty Exchange website.[7][8]
On August 7, 2014, Royalty Exchange closed its first ever multi-unit auction, a type of auction where the asset is securitized or divided into multiple units allowing for numerous buyers to bid on and win small or large amounts of the asset. The auction consisted of producer royalties for 11 tracks recorded and performed by the alternative rock band, 3 Doors Down.[9]
On August 13, 2014, Royalty Exchange announced its partnership with Fender Music Foundation, a non-profit organization that supports the growth of music education through donation of instruments and equipment to schools, after-school programs and music therapy programs.[10] The partnership provides a new platform for revenue-based donations made by songwriters, publishers and performers via their royalty rights auctioned through Royalty Exchange.  Both a percentage of the standard seller auction fee and ongoing administration fee is also donated to the Fender Music Foundation.[11]
In September 2014, Royalty Exchange closed its first renewable energy auction.  The online auction consisted of royalty interests to the electricity gross revenue production from 2 geothermal plants owned by Berkshire Hathaway, operated by MidAmerican Energy’s CalEnergy in California. [11]
Royalty Exchange created and rolled out a tool called the Royalty Analysis Tool.  The Royalty Analysis Tool offers royalty owners the ability to generate a personal report of their royalties.  The analysis tool provides a view of PRO royalty data and allows for the royalty owner to view their potential revenue that will accumulate over time.  The Royalty Analysis Tool supports the following providers: ASCAP, BMI, SESAC and The Orchard. [12][13]
Since Royalty Exchange first was formed in 2011, the company has been featured in CNN, Billboard, Forbes, Yahoo! Finance and USA Today, as well as on Bloomberg Television, Fox Business, the Huffington Post, Music Row Magazine and BestThinking.com.

